man <b>Perschall</b>, a variant of <b>Parschall</b> (see   Parshall  ); alternatively, a variant of <b>Perschel</b>, from a pet form of <b>Persch</b>, a short form of   Berthold   or   Peter   in the border area with Czechia."],"variants":[{"name":"Parshall","meanings":["Americanized form of South German <b>Parschall</b>, a variant of <b>Parschalk</b>, a status name for a freeholder (a freeman with few service obligations), from Middle High German <i>bar</i> ‘naked’, ‘free from, apparent’ + <i>schalk</i> ‘servant, man’. See   Pershall  .","English: variant of   Pearsall  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William De Pershale was born in 1092, his father, Robert FitzGilbert de Corbeil, was 17 and his mother, Ormunda de Lumley, was 21. He had at least 1 son with Ellen Broughton."},"et":{"1092–":"1092–Surnud","1092–Male":"1092–Surnud","1118–1167":"1118–1167","1120–Male":"1120–Surnud","1094–Female":"1094–Surnud","1116–Male":"1116–Surnud","1075–1087":"1075–1087","1072–Female":"1072–Surnud","1118":"1118","1116":"1116","1167":"1167","1087":"1087","1120":"1120","1075":"1075","1072":"1072","1094":"1094","1092":"1092","Abt 1091":"umbes 1091","Corbeil, Marne, Champagne-Ardenne, France":"Corbeil, Marne, Champagne-Ardenne, Prants